Q2: Joining and Grouping

Below we provide 2 datasets also from the Gapminder organization. The first countries is an index of all countries tracked by the organization, including their name, location, region, etc. The second dataset provides a set of development metrics for each country for the year 2021. For this question weâ€™ll consider the Gini index, which is a measure of economic inequality within a country (higher means more unequal). Use these two datasets together to answer the following question:

Which World bank region had the highest economic inequality in 2021? (Averaged over the countries in each region)

co2 = pd.read_csv('data/co2.csv')[['country', '2021']].rename(columns={'2021': 'co2'}).set_index('country')
gini = pd.read_csv('data/gini.csv')[['country', '2021']].rename(columns={'2021': 'gini'}).set_index('country')
hdi = pd.read_csv('data/hdi_human_development_index.csv')[['country', '2021']].rename(columns={'2021': 'hdi'}).set_index('country')
income = pd.read_csv('data/income.csv')[['country', '2021']].rename(columns={'2021': 'income'}).set_index('country')
lex = pd.read_csv('data/lex.csv')[['country', '2021']].rename(columns={'2021': 'lex'}).set_index('country')

countries = pd.read_csv('data/countries.csv').set_index('name')
data = co2.join(gini).join(hdi).join(income).join(lex)

Q4: Plotting density in 2 dimensions

The data below contains a secret message, in this case, just a letter of the alphabet. Unfortunately the data contains too much noise for the letter to be read effectively, as shown in the scatterplot below.

data = pd.read_csv('data/letter.csv')
ggplot() + geom_point(data=data, mapping=aes(x='x', y='y')) + coord_fixed()

Replot the data using a 2D histogram or 2D density plot to reveal the hidden letter.

You may need to adjust the color scale or number of bins to make the letter legible.

What does the visualization you made suggest about the dependence or independence of the variables \(X\) and \(Y\)

  • Across the whole space?
  • In the region \(x \in [-2, -1]\)?

Recall that two variables are independent if \(p(x, y) = p(x)p(y)\)
